==English==

{{wikipedia|Future}}

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|futurus|futūrus|lang=la}}, irregular future active participle of {{term|sum||I am|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|bhū-|lang=ine-pro}}, {{recons|bʰew-||to become, be|lang=ine-pro}}. Cognate with {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|beo|bēo|I become, I will be, I am|lang=ang}}. More at {{l|en|be}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ˈfjuːtʃə/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/"fju:tS@/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈfjuːtʃɚ/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/"fju:tS@`/}}
* {{audio|en-us-future.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|uːtʃə(ɹ)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|-}}

# The [[time]] [[ahead]]; those [[moment]]s [[yet]] to be [[experience]]d.
# Something that will happen in moments yet to come.
# Goodness in what is yet to come/Something to look forward to.
#: ''There is no '''future''' in dwelling on the past.''
# {{context|grammar|lang=en}} Verb tense used to talk about events that will happen in the future; [[future tense]].
# {{context|finance|lang=en}} An [[agreement]] between two parties that one will sell the other a specific commodity at a specific later date and a specific price.

====Usage notes====
* {{sense|finance}} The one who agrees to, at a future date, sell the commodity is considered to be selling the future; the other buys it.

====Coordinate terms====
* {{sense|finance}} [[forward]]

